"Emperor" Bob Hudson (born Robert Howard Holmes on October 7, 1929 in Erie, Pennsylvania) started in radio while serving in the United States Air Force in Anchorage, Alaska.
He was consistently ranked among the top 10 DJs in Southern California from 1963 until his retirement in 1988.

Hudson worked at a variety of LA radio stations, including KRLA, KFWB, KBLA, KEZY, KFI and KGBS, initially coming to prominence when he replaced Bob Eubanks as morning DJ on KRLA in the spring of 1963.
In 1966, Billboard ranked Hudson #1 in his morning drive time slot.
Hudson was featured in The Emperor, a short film made by George Lucas in 1967 when Lucas was a student at USC film school.
He recorded one comedy album with Bobby "Boris" Pickett (of "Monster Mash" fame), The Hollyweird Squares (Dore, 1976), and later teamed with disc jockey Dave (Hull) Judson for Who's on First?
Between 1976 and 1978 (no specific date was given), Hudson attempted to record material for his stint as guest host of Casey Kasem's American Top 40 one week.

Hudson died on September 20, 1997, aged 67, and was survived by his former wife, Joanne Holmes, four children: Tom, Colleen, Mike and Jay, and grandchildren Jenette, Bethany, Elizabeth, Kathleen, Chris, Pat, Rachael, Emily and John.
Ron Landry (b. October 24, 1934) worked at several radio stations in Virginia before becoming the morning host on WDRC in Hartford, CT and then WBZ in Boston.
He and fellow comedy writer Tom Biener recorded "Comedy Album" for the Universal label in 1989.
Landry died of cancer on September 16, 2002 at age 67.
